[{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">(12 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A hydrogen atom can be modeled as a single electron in a circular orbit around a stationary proton. Some properties of the atom can be explained by treating the proton and electron as particles and using classical mechanics and electrostatics. Other properties can be explained using the standing wave model of the electron.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"ai\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) The energy of a hydrogen atom in state <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n\"><math alttext=\"n\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is given by <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub n equals, negative, open parenthesis, 13.6 electron volts, close parenthesis, divided by n squared\"><math alttext=\"E sub n equals, negative, open parenthesis, 13.6 electron volts, close parenthesis, divided by n squared\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>13.6</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">i. Determine the energy of a hydrogen atom in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> state.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"aii\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. The electric potential energy of a hydrogen atom in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> state is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative 3.02 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"negative 3.02 electron volts\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>3.02</mn><mtext> </mtext><mtext> eV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> . Using classical mechanics and electrostatics, calculate the orbital radius of the electron for this state in meters.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:aiii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"aiii\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">iii. Calculate the kinetic energy of the electron when the hydrogen atom is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> state.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:aiv part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"aiv\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">iv. Calculate the speed of the electron when the atom is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> state.<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:bi part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"bi\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) The standing wave model uses the de Broglie wavelength of the electron.</p>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">i. Calculate the de Broglie wavelength of the electron in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> state of a hydrogen atom.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:bii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"bii\">\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. Describe the relationship between the wavelength of the electron and the circumference of its orbit that is used in the standing wave model.<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR188259","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) The circumference of the electron orbit can be calculated from the radius of the orbit found in part (a)(ii). Is the relationship between your values of the de Broglie wavelength from part (b)(i) and the circumference of the orbit consistent with your response in (b)(ii) ? Support your answer.</p></div>\n"}]